english:
  title: On a Painting of Li the Banished Immortal Boating on the White Lotus Pond
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A cool breeze dispels the thick summer heat,
    Ripples pucker the Great Liquid's surface to jade.
    White lotuses in the pond drift fragrance everywhere—
    It clings to the twelve vermillion railings.

    Among drinkers a celestial, among men a hero,
    Yet gold tortoise seals trap him in wine's embrace.
    His eyes bloom with visions, falling down a well,
    As Li Mountain's walls shrink to less than a hair.

    The Palace Attendant receives his decree, turns the orchid boat,
    Through the somber cassia trees, into Gold Gate's shadow.
    He swaggers with shoulder shrug and sidelong glance,
    His robe half-slipped, the crested cap upon his head nearly tumbling.

    Past crystal halls, past jade steps, past the imperial dais,
    Guided to the very depths of azure clouds.
    Ice-cold water pools like cream in jade bowls—
    Splashed upon his drunken face, his spirit revives.

    Brush in hand, ten verses of the Clear Harmony song,
    Each word a pearl, each phrase a jewel.
    A thousand fingers before the hall play the strings,
    First presenting the poem, then the new melody.

    The Son of Heaven smiles and bestows the brocade robe,
    Yet he removes his boots in shame—the general's plight.
    But favor flows like water, never to return,
    And in distant Yelong, only the gibbons weep.

    Such is the way of this human world—
    Not Li the Banished Immortal alone in Tang's day.
    Who with divine brush captured this image so true?
    Within a simple scroll, the very truth of those times.

    Once gone, the hero cannot be summoned back,
    Only this fervent sigh before the wine cup—three times over.
  footnotes:
    - Li Bai (李白), known as 'Li the Banished Immortal' (李謫仙), was an 8th-century Tang dynasty poet of legendary reputation. This painting depicts a famous episode of his life.
    - The 'Great Liquid' (太液) refers to the royal ponds of Chang'an, the Tang capital.
    - '''Yelong'' (夜郞) references the remote frontier region where Li Bai was banished, a punishment that haunted his later years.'
